<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1908-10-09T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1908-10-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="709" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d709">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 10044/74.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Ambassador <persName type="from">Leishman</persName>
                                to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Constantinople</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1908-10-09"><hi rend="italic">October 9,
                                1908</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>(Mr. Leishman reports that, although rumors of war continue to circulate
                            and considerable uncertainty and anxiety prevail, he is still hopeful
                            that recourse to arms will be avoided, as the leaders of the
                            constitutional party continue to act in the most conservative manner and
                            are evidently doing everything in their power to calm the bellicose
                            spirit of the army, much to the discomfiture of the reactionaries.)</p>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>